  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Empirical evidence in (Mishra et al., 2013, Fig. 5) shows that substituting Θ by a diagonal matrix Θ d, as done in AdaLoRA (Zhang et al., 2023), can adversely affect convergence, potentially because of the presence of non-strict saddles in the loss landscape (Levin et al., 2024).",
    "These spurious stationary points can be removed by a parameterization with positive-definite Θ s (Levin et al., 2024, Prop. 2.10).",
    "Our PoLAR parameterization poses no constraints on Θ.",
    "It thus avoids computational overheads associated with enforcing positive-definiteness (e.g., matrix exponentials), yet still ensures global convergence.",
    "Lastly, we extend our analysis to the symmetric matrix factorization problem in Appendix E, where we prove last-iterate convergence with complexity O κ 4 log(1/ϵ)."
  ],
